"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, as a market gardener, I'm going to focus a lot of my garden space on the ground on perennial herbs. In this bed over here, I have mint grows crazy up here or down here in Houston. So I'm growing a lot of it, very fragrant. Everyone can use more mint. Over there, I have oregano. Over there I have rosemary. You look at this bed, it's well occupied. It's completely filled up. The perennial herbs are going nuts. Over in another bed, I have a bunch of parsley that's going to go very well in this climate. I've grown it before and it kind of carpets things out. And I'm not only going to try to sell this because it's easy to sell, and I'm just cutting down leaves. I'm not trying to harvest any fruit. Herbs are just about growing leaves. So it's literally the easiest thing you can do. And you can always be just churning out a lot of it. When you have a big plant, cutting a little bit of wage week is just going to promote more of its growth. And you know, it's it's all beneficial. But I have one of these great big plants, but it's not just for a market gardener. Whenever someone's asking me about gardening, I always tell them, hey, just grab a small plot. If you have one bed you can grow, if you have a little space you can grow, cultivate cultivate the decay cycle in that little spot, making your own little compost or doing whatever you have to do, get that little cultivated spot of the decay cycle, and then grow herbs there. Because herbs are the easiest things to do. You can jump in with both feet. Not a hard thing to do. You're only growing leaves, but also you can incorporate these foods into every meal. Once you start getting into it, you you like going to your little herb bed before each meal. You know, this is kind of the fun of it. And so once you get more into that habit, that's a great way to integrate into that's a great way to integrate small amounts of living foods into every meal, and then you build up to more and more of it. But herbs are a great thing for getting started with it, and I'm gonna really try to promote that at my farmer's market booth and grow a lot of it in my garden and just see what happens. Oh, and also one of the things I'm also gonna promote is these are aromatics. So when you get them, put them in a a vase with some water or whatever, cup, put it on the counter, and let those aromatics work. Let them be fragrant and then use them for your food as you use them, but leave them out, put them in water as they start to wilt, of course, use them up, but they'll they'll last a couple days over in that water, most of them. And some of them you might have to put in the fridge and that. But like using them as aromatics more than just cooking, but just kind of nice fragrance, it's great. Anyway, thanks y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody, as a market gardener, I'm going to focus a lot of my garden space on the ground on perennial herbs.\",\n      \"start\": 0.32,\n      \"end\": 9.44,\n      \"duration\": 9.12,\n      \"confidence\": 0.994,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.32,\n          \"end\": 0.56,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 0.979\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.56,\n          \"end\": 0.64,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 0.999\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 0.88,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 0.88,\n          \"end\": 1.12,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 1.12,\n          \"end\": 1.28,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \",\",\n          \"st